<subSubSection id="B186655BFFBA590D589AC99FB53FFB39" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="F92336D0FFBA590D589AC99FB53FFB39" blockId="12.[146,770,1772,1938]" lastBlockId="12.[818,1443,1126,1530]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<emphasis id="CBE8EAC2FFBA590D589AC99FB19DF8EB" box="[146,454,1772,1792]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
Comments. 
<taxonomicName id="3E9C4D53FFBA590D590AC99FB19DF8EB" baseAuthorityName="Schaus" baseAuthorityYear="1905" box="[258,454,1772,1792]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Epidesma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aurimacula">Epidesma aurimacula</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="61A72A55FFBA590D59DCC99FB225F8EB" box="[468,638,1772,1792]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="13.[146,172,1785,1802]" captionTargetBox="[186,1409,158,1748]" captionTargetId="figure-2@13.[171,1417,147,1750]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="Fig.12. Selection of species of Epidesmato demonstrate their variation and similarity with respect to wing pattern versus male genitalia.(A‒F) Epidesma aurimacula syn. nov. from Panguana/Peru (A, B), from French Guiana (C, D), from Bolivia (E), from Venezuela (F). (G) E. klagesi. (H) E. ursula from French Guiana. (I) E. sp. nr ursula from Costa Rica.(K) E. sp.nr klagesi from Costa Rica.(L) E. nr crameri from Peru.(M) Recently transferred from Epidesma (Laguerre 2019): Aphymolis similis; left upperside,right underside;genitalia dorsal,ventral,phallus from left to right. Scale bars = 1 cm for moths,1 mm for genitalia. See also Fig. 4." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5384277" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5384277/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Fig. 12A and D‒F</figureCitation>
) and 
<taxonomicName id="3E9C4D53FFBA590D5ABCC99EB359F914" baseAuthorityName="Rothschild" baseAuthorityYear="1912" box="[692,770,1773,1791]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Epidesma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="parva">
<emphasis id="CBE8EAC2FFBA590D5ABCC99EB359F914" box="[692,770,1773,1791]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">E. parva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="61A72A55FFBA590D5891C87AB140F8F6" box="[153,283,1801,1821]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="13.[146,172,1785,1802]" captionTargetBox="[186,1409,158,1748]" captionTargetId="figure-2@13.[171,1417,147,1750]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="Fig.12. Selection of species of Epidesmato demonstrate their variation and similarity with respect to wing pattern versus male genitalia.(A‒F) Epidesma aurimacula syn. nov. from Panguana/Peru (A, B), from French Guiana (C, D), from Bolivia (E), from Venezuela (F). (G) E. klagesi. (H) E. ursula from French Guiana. (I) E. sp. nr ursula from Costa Rica.(K) E. sp.nr klagesi from Costa Rica.(L) E. nr crameri from Peru.(M) Recently transferred from Epidesma (Laguerre 2019): Aphymolis similis; left upperside,right underside;genitalia dorsal,ventral,phallus from left to right. Scale bars = 1 cm for moths,1 mm for genitalia. See also Fig. 4." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5384277" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5384277/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Fig.12B and C</figureCitation>
) differ in the expression of the oblique yellow forewing band and, in particular, in their hindwing pattern which is completely black in 
<taxonomicName id="3E9C4D53FFBA590D58EFC836B163F8BC" baseAuthorityName="Rothschild" baseAuthorityYear="1912" box="[231,312,1861,1879]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Epidesma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="parva">
<emphasis id="CBE8EAC2FFBA590D58EFC836B163F8BC" box="[231,312,1861,1879]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">E. parva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but exhibits a white or yellow central patch of variable size on both upper- and underside in 
<taxonomicName id="3E9C4D53FFBA590D5A43C811B296F89E" baseAuthorityName="Schaus" baseAuthorityYear="1905" box="[587,717,1889,1909]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Epidesma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aurimacula">
<emphasis id="CBE8EAC2FFBA590D5A43C811B296F89E" box="[587,717,1889,1909]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">E. aurimacula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Fine white or yellow crosslines on the upperside of the abdomen separate the segments clearly. Their genitalia are identical (
<figureCitation id="61A72A55FFBA590D5CE5CB15B52FFB91" box="[1261,1396,1126,1146]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="13.[146,172,1785,1802]" captionTargetBox="[186,1409,158,1748]" captionTargetId="figure-2@13.[171,1417,147,1750]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="Fig.12. Selection of species of Epidesmato demonstrate their variation and similarity with respect to wing pattern versus male genitalia.(A‒F) Epidesma aurimacula syn. nov. from Panguana/Peru (A, B), from French Guiana (C, D), from Bolivia (E), from Venezuela (F). (G) E. klagesi. (H) E. ursula from French Guiana. (I) E. sp. nr ursula from Costa Rica.(K) E. sp.nr klagesi from Costa Rica.(L) E. nr crameri from Peru.(M) Recently transferred from Epidesma (Laguerre 2019): Aphymolis similis; left upperside,right underside;genitalia dorsal,ventral,phallus from left to right. Scale bars = 1 cm for moths,1 mm for genitalia. See also Fig. 4." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5384277" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5384277/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Fig. 12A and B</figureCitation>
) and sequences of specimens with either pattern from 
<collectingCountry id="818B7640FFBA590D5CEDCBF7B54BFB7C" box="[1253,1296,1156,1175]" name="Peru" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Peru</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="818B7640FFBA590D5D1FCBF7B5C5FB73" box="[1303,1438,1156,1176]" name="French Guiana" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">French Guiana</collectingCountry>
, Columbia, and 
<collectingCountry id="818B7640FFBA590D5BB4CBD2B3ABFB5E" box="[956,1008,1185,1205]" name="Brazil" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Brazil</collectingCountry>
form BIN BOLD:AAP4004 (
<figureCitation id="61A72A55FFBA590D5CFFCBD2B56FFB5E" box="[1271,1332,1185,1205]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="14.[147,174,1459,1476]" captionTargetBox="[147,1442,151,1423]" captionTargetId="figure-273@14.[146,1442,147,1423]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="Fig. 13. Neighbor-joining distance tree of 27 COI sequences of Vanewrightia gen.nov. and 38 of its neighbors from BOLDSYSTEMS (2019) with BIN BOLD codes. Distances (normalized to 1) are given below each branch (omitted if &lt;0.002) and bootstrap supports above each branch (in bold, only if&gt;70%) obtained with MEGA7 (Kumar et al. 2016). For Vanewrightia, the collection sites are highlighted by colors. Scale bar = 1%." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5384279" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5384279/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Fig. 13</figureCitation>
). Therefore, we propose 
<taxonomicName id="3E9C4D53FFBA590D5B97CBCCB3B0FB3A" baseAuthorityName="Rothschild" baseAuthorityYear="1912" box="[927,1003,1215,1233]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Epidesma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="parva">
<emphasis id="CBE8EAC2FFBA590D5B97CBCCB3B0FB3A" box="[927,1003,1215,1233]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">E. parva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to be a junior synonym of 
<taxonomicName id="3E9C4D53FFBA590D5CD7CBCCB505FB39" baseAuthorityName="Schaus" baseAuthorityYear="1905" box="[1247,1374,1214,1234]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Epidesma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aurimacula">
<emphasis id="CBE8EAC2FFBA590D5CD7CBCCB505FB39" box="[1247,1374,1214,1234]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">E. aurimacula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="B186655BFFBA590D5B5ACBADB46CFA11" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" type="reference_group">
<paragraph id="F92336D0FFBA590D5B5ACBADB4C3FA49" blockId="12.[818,1443,1126,1530]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<taxonomicName id="3E9C4D53FFBA590D5B5ACBADB440FB19" baseAuthorityName="Schaus" baseAuthorityYear="1905" box="[850,1051,1246,1266]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Epidesma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aurimacula">
<emphasis id="CBE8EAC2FFBA590D5B5ACBADB440FB19" box="[850,1051,1246,1266]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Epidesma aurimacula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
thus is another polymorphic species that visits PA-baits (personal observation). As in 
<taxonomicName id="3E9C4D53FFBA590D5CD3CB8EB56EFAFB" authorityName="Boppré &amp; Grados &amp; Laguerre &amp; Monzón" authorityYear="2020" box="[1243,1333,1276,1296]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Vanewrightia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kiesela">
<emphasis id="CBE8EAC2FFBA590D5CD3CB8EB56EFAFB" box="[1243,1333,1276,1296]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">V. kiesela</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, its delimitation cannot finally be given because the full range of variation remains unknown. Perhaps, further species, e.g., 
<taxonomicName id="3E9C4D53FFBA590D5D2ECA44B38DFA83" authority="(Hampson, 1905)" baseAuthorityName="Hampson" baseAuthorityYear="1905" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Epidesma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albicincta">
<emphasis id="CBE8EAC2FFBA590D5D2ECA44B5F9FAA1" box="[1318,1442,1334,1354]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">E. albicincta</emphasis>
(Hampson, 1905)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="3E9C4D53FFBA590D5C0FCA26B4A2FA83" authority="(Zerny, 1931)" baseAuthorityName="Zerny" baseAuthorityYear="1931" box="[1031,1273,1364,1384]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Epidesma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="josioides">
<emphasis id="CBE8EAC2FFBA590D5C0FCA26B42AFA83" box="[1031,1137,1364,1384]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">E. josioides</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="9D0D4B21FFBA590D5C88CA27B4AAFA83" author="Zerny, H." box="[1152,1265,1364,1384]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" pagination="1 - 27" refId="ref15928" refString="Zerny, H. 1931. Beitrage zur Kenntnis der Syntomiden. Dtsch. Entomol. Z. Iris 45: 1 - 27." type="journal article" year="1931">Zerny, 1931</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
are synonyms for 
<taxonomicName id="3E9C4D53FFBA590D5B3ACA01B3EEFA6E" baseAuthorityName="Schaus" baseAuthorityYear="1905" box="[818,949,1393,1413]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Epidesma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aurimacula">
<emphasis id="CBE8EAC2FFBA590D5B3ACA01B3EEFA6E" box="[818,949,1393,1413]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">E. aurimacula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(their hindwing shapes might be an indication), but this can only be clarified by barcoding.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F92336D0FFBA590D5B5ACADFB46CFA11" blockId="12.[818,1443,1126,1530]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
One might argue, 
<taxonomicName id="3E9C4D53FFBA590D5C28CADEB4F4FA2B" baseAuthorityName="Schaus" baseAuthorityYear="1905" box="[1056,1199,1452,1472]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Epidesma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aurimacula">
<emphasis id="CBE8EAC2FFBA590D5C28CADEB4F4FA2B" box="[1056,1199,1452,1472]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">E. aurimacula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
should be treated as 
<taxonomicName id="3E9C4D53FFBA590D5B3ACABAB3F6FA36" authorityName="Boppré &amp; Grados &amp; Laguerre &amp; Monzón" authorityYear="2020" box="[818,941,1481,1501]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Vanewrightia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="CBE8EAC2FFBA590D5B3ACABAB3F6FA36" box="[818,941,1481,1501]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Vanewrightia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, or 
<taxonomicName id="3E9C4D53FFBA590D5BDACAB9B472FA36" authorityName="Boppré &amp; Grados &amp; Laguerre &amp; Monzón" authorityYear="2020" box="[978,1065,1481,1501]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Vanewrightia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kiesela">
<emphasis id="CBE8EAC2FFBA590D5BDACAB9B472FA36" box="[978,1065,1481,1501]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">V. kiesela</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<emphasis id="CBE8EAC2FFBA590D5C5FCAB9B430FA37" box="[1111,1131,1482,1500]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">V.</emphasis>
sp. nov., 
<taxonomicName id="3E9C4D53FFBA590D5CC9CABAB578FA36" authorityName="Boppré &amp; Grados &amp; Laguerre &amp; Monzón" authorityYear="2020" box="[1217,1315,1481,1501]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Vanewrightia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kiesela">
aff. 
<emphasis id="CBE8EAC2FFBA590D5CEDCABAB578FA36" box="[1253,1315,1481,1501]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">kiesela</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as 
<taxonomicName id="3E9C4D53FFBA590D5D4ACABAB5C7FA36" authorityName="Hubner" authorityYear="1819" box="[1346,1436,1481,1501]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Epidesma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="CBE8EAC2FFBA590D5D4ACABAB5C7FA36" box="[1346,1436,1481,1501]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Epidesma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; this issue is discussed below.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
